TITLE: North Korea aims to have world’s most powerful nuclear force, leader Kim says
SUMMARY: Kim inspected a test of the country's largest intercontinental ballistic missile and pledged to counter what he called U.S. nuclear threats

TITLE: 49 arrested as police bust European cocaine ‘super cartel'
SUMMARY: Law enforcement authorities in six countries joined forces to take down the ring of drug traffickers controlling about one-third of the cocaine trade in Europe, Europol said

TITLE: Surgeons work with flashlight as Russian strikes batter Ukraine's power grid
SUMMARY: Scheduled operations are being postponed, patient records are unavailable because of internet outages, and paramedics have had to use flashlights to examine patients in darkened apartments

TITLE: Russia postpones nuclear arms control negotiations with the U.S.
SUMMARY: A State Department spokesperson said Russia had postponed talks aimed at resuming nuclear arms inspections, but they were working to reschedule

TITLE: South Korea's LGBTQ community confronts crushing headwinds in fight for equality
SUMMARY: Conservative lawmakers and religious leaders have contributed to activists’ lengthy and unsuccessful attempts to pass a comprehensive nondiscrimination bill

TITLE: WHO renames monkeypox as mpox, citing racism concerns
SUMMARY: It appears to be the first time the agency has tried to rechristen a disease decades after it was named

TITLE: South Korea extradites suspect in New Zealand suitcase murders
SUMMARY: The woman arrived in Auckland two months after she was arrested following the discovery of the bodies of two long-dead children in abandoned suitcases

TITLE: Australia argues against ‘endangered’ status for Great Barrier Reef
SUMMARY: The environment minister said the recommendation was a reflection on Australia’s previous conservative government and that the new center-left government has already addressed concerns about the UNESCO site

TITLE: Myanmar detention was ‘hell,’ says freed Japanese filmmaker
SUMMARY: Toru Kubota, who was jailed for nearly four months, called on Tokyo to take a tougher stance against human rights abuses in the military-controlled country

TITLE: China’s lockdown protests spread to campuses and cities abroad
SUMMARY: Expatriate dissidents and students staged small-scale events in cities like London, Paris, Tokyo and Sydney, in a rare instance of Chinese people uniting in anger at home and abroad
